g.text: Efficacy of a Single Dose of
MERS-CoV seronegative and seropositive camels received a single intramuscular dose of ChAdOx1
MERS, a replication-deficient adenoviral vectored vaccine expressing MERS-CoV spike protein, with
further groups receiving control vaccinations. Infectious camels with active naturally acquired MERS-
CoV infection, were co-housed with the vaccinated camels at a ratio of 1:2 (infected:vaccinated); nasal
discharge and virus titres were monitored for 14 days. Overall, the vaccination reduced virus shedding
camels were enhancedby the vaccine; these camels had a higher average age than seronegative. Older
seronegative camels responded more strongly to vaccination than younger animals; and neutralising
antibodies were detected in nasal swabs. Further work is required to optimise vaccine regimens for
Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) was first identified in 2012 from a pneumonic
patient who subsequently died in Saudi Arabia. Since its emergence, the virus has infected more than 2200 indi-
. Outbreaks occurred mainly in the Arabian Peninsula in large crowded hospitals with
one large outbreak in the Republic of Korea
. Although bats have been proposed as a possible natural reservoir
, dromedary camels are the only confirmed animal host so far. More than half (54.9%) of human
primary cases have reported contact with camels
and the index patient in the Korean outbreak travelled back
from the Gulf countries where MERS-CoV is endemic and circulating in dromedary camels
